Pop a deep #saucepan{} (with a tight-fitting #lid{}) on medium heat with a drizzle of @oil{}. When hot, add the @ginger puree{15%grams} and stir-fry for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @basmati rice{150%grams} until coated, ~{1%minute}. Add @salt{1/4%tsp} and the @water for the rice{200%milliliter} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the #pan{} from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

In the meantime, peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Trim the @green beans{80%grams}.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @diced British chicken breast{260%grams} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Fry until golden brown on the outside and cooked through, ~{8-10%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging. It's cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When the chicken has ~{5%minutes} left, stir through the green beans and continue to cook for the remaining amount of time.

Add the garlic and @tikka masala paste{75%grams} to the chicken pan and cook until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir through the @tomato passata{1%carton}, @chicken stock paste{10%grams}, @sugar for the sauce{1/2%tsp} and @water for the sauce{100%milliliter} and simmer until thickened slightly, ~{2-3%minutes}.

When everything's ready, fluff up the rice with a #fork{}.

Taste your curry and season with salt and pepper if needed. Add a splash of water if it's a little too thick.

Share your rice between your #serving bowls{}.

Top with your chicken tikka style curry.

Enjoy!